The transition area between sand and muck is quite extensive, as were shown on the map. This area was colored a mixture of yellow, representing sand, and brown, representing muck. At the East end of the lake the marl bottom type grades into muck and sand and this area is represented on the map by a mixture of yellow, brown and green. This mixed bottom (marl, muck and sand) type was found, only in T26N, R15W sections 22, 21 and 15. The bottom type considered marl was of a peculiar consistency not in common with true marl. A sample of this bottom preserved for verification was identified as marl.

No natural reproduction of walleyes but survival of stocked walleyes very good. Northern pike population seems to be down. Bluegills small but chunky. Not many fish collected in the survey. Recommend night electrofishing survey to complement the netting survey and also to better assess the largemouth bass population. Lake may be good prospect for stocking walleye fingerlings. See below for further remarks. Gillnets removed after one night.
data:
No natural reproduction of walleyes but survival and growth of stocked walleyes very good. Northern pike population seems to be down. Bluegills small but chunky. Not many fish collected in the survey. Recommend night electrofishing survey to complement the netting survey and also to better assess the largemouth bass population. Lake may be good prospect for stocking walleye fingerlings. See below for further remarks. Gillnets removed after one night. 
Mean growth index of all panfish and largemouth bass below state average. Growth of northern pike appears good. Mean growth index of Age V & VI walleyes is 1.6 inches above state average.
